   "source": [
    "# Line Graph\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook demonstrates how to create a simple line graph using Python's `matplotlib`. We'll start with sample data and then show you how to load and visualize your own dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Basic Line Graph"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Step 1: Import Libraries\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "# Step 2: Create Sample Data\n",
    "x = np.linspace(0, 23, 2*24)\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "noise = np.random.uniform(-1, 1.5, size=x.shape)\n",
    "y = 20 + 8 * np.sin((x - 9) * np.pi / 12) + noise\n",
    "\n",
    "# Step 3: Plotting the Basic Line Graph\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "plt.plot(x, y, label='sin(x)', color='blue', linewidth=1)\n",
    "plt.title('Basic Line Graph')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('X-axis')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Y-axis')\n",
    "plt.ylim(10,30)\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
